December 2008 notes

Coyotes have been happening here recently. This is one of four that emerged from the vegetation with the coyote brush in the background. One coyote had a gopher and another had its eye on a nearby hunting Great Egret. The egret sensing the unwanted attention escaped the area. My first evidence of the actual presence of the coyotes were from seeing scat and hearing their calls each time a siren had passed.

description: Found on wood, under pines in mixed woods.

Found in redwood, and D. fir needle duff.

Some unknown Xeromphalina that I have been finding for a few years up in the Mendocino area now. I put this under the scope last year, and it has amyloid small ellipsiod smooth spores. The funny character of these, as a Xeromphalina, is that the gills are notched, not decurrent. Not extremely common, but a couple seem to be found it each year up there (if people are inspired to look for these little guys…).

Collection found by Nate Seagraves.

These were a new for me, they had white gills under the thick woolly veils.

Found on ground in mossy areas with pine needle duff.

Probably not the best name for these, but I’m not sure how to put better names on these little guys.
Stinky, bad, light rotten vegetables with garlic.
Found under pines, some D. fir close, but not too close.

This one seem fairly different from S. caerulescens, the veil is fairly orange and viscid, and the cap is fairly red-orange-brown, so it is fairly clearly S. ponderosus. One of things in the Thiers description of this species was that the stipe base bruises green, where S. caerulescens stipe base bruises blue. I’ve seen the blue, but not the green from the description. So, I cut this one in half, and bruised one half from the base up to the cap. One thing is that the flesh here is more yellow, compared to S. caerulescens, which I’ve seen as off-white creamy to light tan. The bruising here was very slight, and only at the base. I would say that the bruising was actually blue, but so light against the yellow flesh, that it appears somewhat green.

Found under D. fir and redwood.

Monster ones found this year, to go along with other monster sized fungus found this year. The larger cups were 3-4 inches in diameter.
Taste bitter, light grey-blue-green reaction to KOH (mostly grey).

A few of these brought in, and they were very large, the bigger one here was like 10 inches high there. These didn’t bruise at all, and had no odor. We cooked these up that night as a set of mushroom appetizers of different species, these were pretty good, better than I expected.
With a strong odor of almonds to marascino cherries, not quite pure almond odor, something sweeter than that.

Found in moss on the ground, under pine, D. fir, some tan oak was maybe near enough.

I was a bit excited to find these, it was the first time finding these for California for me, nice to see. Mixed in with a lot of Mycena, and kinda hard to see. I saw the small central black spot, and then turning over the id became clear, not Mycena.
A mostly white Ramaria with yellow tips, and red staining near the base. Id’ed from the Ramaria of the Pacific Northwest book.
Found under mixed forest, pine, D. fir, madrone, tanoak, scrub…
In mixed forest, pine, d. fir, madrone, tan oak, scrub…

These are usually fairly rare for the FFSC forays, this was the first one in five years or so, and this was a good one brought in. I heard that for the Arora forays at the end of Nov. at least one of these comes in each year. Kinda suggests that these are a more early season mushroom, and is usually gone by Dec. Either that or Arora and others pick them all and leave none for us to find…

Found under mixed forest, pine, D. fir, madrone, scrub.

Not sure if these are P. melaleucus and P. atratus, and I’m not sure how to tell the difference…

Different forms of this variable ’shroom. A few came in this time, and they were different in each collection. Here is a more standard brown to purple, and a faded off-white to light lilac, to demonstrate the range.
Found in mixed D. fir, redwood area.
Found on D. fir log. Id’ed with Arora with the reddish stains in age, and grey.
Found with moss and small woody debris, under pine, D. fir and tan oak.
Found in a mixed D. fir, redwood area of Jackson State Forest.
Found in mossy area, near grass, under pines.

A number of different collections were brought in. It seems like it was a fairly good year for these. Also at the Santa Cruz Fair there were a large number of random dark Leptonias came in. Someday it might be nice to actually be able to id any of these to species…

Found under pines. A fairly good year for this one, found in a number of places, not in great numbers but still there more than some years past. Found a young one here, which shows the hairy margin well.
Found under pines. Latently, but strongly, acrid.
Found under pine, D. fir, tan oak.

Found under pines, D. fir. It was a big year for this one, huge. Usually this is a fairly rare one, often missing, or only a few found. Many years it is confused with R. brevipes, and just brushed off. This year, you couldn’t just brush it off, it was everywhere. Many, many caps brought in, including one huge one, about 16 inches in diameter. Later at the Oakland fair, they were everywhere there also, brought in from all places north. Something about this year worked out really well with these, more than many others.
Found under pine, D. fir, tan oak.

Found under pines, D. fir (some tan oak was around, but not that close). First time I’ve seen these up there, and the first time to put them on the list for the Fungus Fed. I show these to John Brown, who has been focusing on Inocybe for a few years now, and he scoffs, “That’s just cinnamomea, I see those every year. They are so common I don’t even write them down.” So there you have it, so common that it has never made it to the species list…

Found by Hugh Smith, I believe he said under pine. These are kinda weird, if found in the mountains in the spring, I would call it an easy id, but wrong place, wrong time. Even with that, I don’t think there is another id for these, except for H. subalpinus, with the all white color, the thick stature, and the fibrous veil. A strange find for the coast in the fall. Hugh mentioned that he found a good sized patch of these, and only brought in this one good sample.

Found under pines. A very good years for these, many brought in by many people. In past years these are either missing or only a few found. I found a few large groupings myself. I include here a photo where I put KOH on the stipe to show the rapid orange reaction.

This is a confusing one found under pines around Mendocino. I think most descriptions have this one as brown in other places in the world. And here I saw a few with the brown cap surface. There are others here with the brown to tan zonate cap. And in the past years this one also gets bright orange and red colors in the cap. A strangely variable mushroom.
Found under pine/ d. fir. Some area had hugh grouping of these this year. One area with over 100 cap in view.
Found under pine and D. fir. Probably not the real H. aurantiacum, but that is what people have been calling it around here for years now.
Found on D. fir log. Found in same place as last year, where I scoped these to make the id.
Found under pine, D. fir, and tan oak.
Under D. fir, redwood, tan oak, and other scrub.

In moss, on the ground, under D. fir.

Not sure which variation of these yet.

Found under D. fir. Found on good patch of these, and I gathered about 30 caps… a little too much. I keep gathering too many of these, they are almost too common, I need to pull back on this species, and concentrate on others. I was looking over Dr. Perry’s thesis on Mycena, and most of his taxa are described from 5-8 specimens. I have way more of this species at this point. Then again, he put 70 taxa in his monograph, and I don’t have that many Galerina yet…
Hugh Smith found these, he told me there were on Tan Oak as far as he knows.

These are kinda odd, they are Crepidotus, but not on wood. These are on grass and small herbaceous stems. They have very viscid and non-hygrophanous caps, need to look at these under the scope at some point…
Id’ed by the bitter viscid cap surface. The cap on the right in the photo was a much older specimen compared to the other two, and it has gome kinda grey in age.
Ok, we’ve been calling these C. mucosus for a few years up there. I think that from Dimi’s work, it looks like there are a couple other similar species, that a seaprated by spore size and shape.

As far as I understand these are what we are calling C. laniger around here. I think from Dimi’s comments I have a little more confidence that this might be true, and then from other comments, I’m not sure this is true at all. It seems that with Corts if I try to id some of them, I’m just opening up myself to get shot down… makes me wonder if any confidence in Cort id’s can get generated here in CA.

ANyway, here is another attempt at a Cort. id…
Usually not seen this late, these are usually seen earlier in the year up there. Probably due to the long dry period before the foray this was able to grow and survive.

This was the first time these were listed as part of the FFSC foray, although I thought I had seen these up there before. I seems these are a fairly rare mushroom this far south, although common in the Pacific Northwest.
A lot! found this year, at least 2 dozen caps brought in, many more left out in the field.

A big year for these. I first id’ed these a few years ago, and I believe they were just ignored before, because since then I’ve seen at least one each year. This year there were about a dozen brought in, and most of them much larger than what had been seen in the past. Also this year a number of these stained blue in the pores and in the flesh when cut. This blue reaction was light, and slow compared to other blue staining species. I hadn’t seen this blue staining in these in the past, usually they don’t stain blue. The blue staining was noted in the Thiers’ monograph, but this was the first time I saw this actually happening.

A few of these were 8-10 inch in diameter, usually they are 3-5 inches in size.

A number of these found this time, fairly common under pines. A few of these were very large, 10-12 inch in diameter in size. There were quite a few species this year that came in with some of the largest examples people had seen.
Various examples of mushrooms that more or less id as A. gemmata.

My second viewing, a day later, of this most unassuming-looking predator.  This is one of a group which are known popularly (in some parts of the world) as "butcher birds."  That's because they are predators -- eating insects, small reptiles, and even other birds.  Apparently that small hook on the bill can cause some damage.

When they have captured an insect or small lizard (and killed it), they often impale their prey on a thorn.  In fact some observers have noticed that if there are no trees or bushes with thorns about -- you won't find shrikes, either.

Huckleberry Botanic Preserve has been hit pretty hard by Sudden Oak Death. There's been quite a bit of oak mortality, and many of the living show symptoms. In the photos here, you can see some: dark weeping wounds, infestation by beetles and the fungus Hypoxylon, and foliar infections on the surrounding CA Bay Laurels. While none of these symptoms are definitive (though the weeping is a very good/bad sign), together they're highly suggestive. To learn more about Sudden Oak Death, go to www.suddenoakdeath.org. To report sightings, go to www.oakmapper.org.
